                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d229">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">814.51/286: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-05-03T11:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1919, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 23, 5 p.m.</p>
                <p>Additional issue of sixty millions paper will make ultimate reform of currency
                    much more difficult and should be prevented if possible. It is left to your
                    discretion to make such representations to President Estrada as you think most
                    likely to dissuade him from signing bill in question, referring to interest
                    which United States feels and has shown in establishing currency of Guatemala on
                    a gold basis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
